{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>The CII protein is a transcription activator, conserved in bacteriophage lambda and related phages, that plays a key role in the decision between lytic or lysogenic phage development. CII is regulated at multiple levels including transcription, translation initiation, mRNA stability, and proteolysis [[cite:PUB00010448]]. Conditions that stabilise cII favour lysogenic development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The lambda CII protein activates three specific promoters, binding to direct repeat sequences rather than the more usual inverted repeats. Structurally, CII is a homotetramer where each monomer is composed of four α helices and a disordered C terminus [[cite:PUB00038382], [cite:PUB00038981]]. The α helical region is responsible for DNA binding and multimerisation. The homotetramer has an unusual spatial arrangement that allows recognition of the direct repeat sequences.</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "1zs4", "name" "Structure of bacteriophage lambda cII protein in complex with DNA"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR010982", "name" "Lambda repressor-like, DNA-binding domain superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"pfam" {"PF05269" "Bacteriophage CII protein"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Transcription activator CII", "short" "Transcrpt_activ_CII"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 4, "domain_architectures" 5, "proteomes" 185, "taxa" 1326, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 1920, "sets" 0, "proteins" 1919, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 1362}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR007933", :literature {"PUB00010448" {"URL" nil, "issue" "23", "authors" ["Kobiler O" "Koby S" "Teff D" "Court D" "Oppenheim AB."], "ISO_journal" "Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A.", "DOI_URL" "http://dx.doi.org/10.1073/pnas.222172499", 